<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
From all other species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Synotis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Synotis" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Synotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. panzhouensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="panzhouensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">S. panzhouensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very distinct in the red-purple pappus. According to our observation of the plants 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">in vivo</emphasis>
, as well as a critical examination of taxa throughout the genus, most species (~50 spp.) have white pappus. Five species in sect. 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. subsp. ser." pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="series" series="Fulvipapposae" species="panzhouensis" subSpecies="ser.">S. ser. Fulvipapposae</taxonomicName>
C.Jeffrey &amp; Y.L.Chen often have white or stramineous pappus, which is consistent with the descriptions reported by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/4110124" author="Jeffrey, C" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="205 - 446" refId="B3" refString="Jeffrey, C, Chen, YL, 1984. Taxonomic studies on the tribe Senecioneae (Compositae) of Eastern Asia. Kew Bulletin 39 (2): 205 - 446, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/4110124" title="Taxonomic studies on the tribe Senecioneae (Compositae) of Eastern Asia." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/4110124" volume="39" year="1984">Jeffrey and Chen (1984)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chen, YL" editor="Chen, YL" journalOrPublisher="77. Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="1 - 326" refId="B1" refString="Chen, YL, 1999. Senecioneae Cass. In: Chen, YL, Ed., Flora Reipublicae Popularis Sinicae, vol. 77. Science Press, Beijing: 1 - 326" title="Senecioneae Cass." volumeTitle="Flora Reipublicae Popularis Sinicae, vol." year="1999">Chen (1999)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Chen, YL" editor="Wu, ZY" journalOrPublisher="20 - 21. Science Press, Beijing &amp; Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="489 - 505" refId="B2" refString="Chen, YL, Nordenstam, B, Jeffrey, C, 2011. Synotis (C.B.Clarke) C.Jeffrey &amp; Y.L.Chen. In: Wu, ZY, Raven, PH, Eds., Flora of China, vol. 20-21. Science Press, Beijing &amp; Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis: 489 - 505" title="Synotis (C. B. Clarke) C. Jeffrey &amp; Y. L. Chen." volumeTitle="Flora of China, vol." year="2011">Chen et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
. The pappus colour of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. vaniotii" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="vaniotii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">S. vaniotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Lévl">Levl</normalizedToken>
.) C.Jeffrey &amp; Y.L.Chen and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. palmatisecta" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="palmatisecta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">S. palmatisecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Y.L.Chen &amp; D.J.Liu were described as rubescent, but this might be the result of inattentive observation, for both of the species were found with white, or rarely pale brown pappus during our field and herbarium observations. It is noteworthy to mention that 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. chenopodiifolia" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="chenopodiifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">S. chenopodiifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(DC.) M.Tang, C.Ren &amp; Q.E.Yang, a species always reported with brown or yellow pappus, has been reported with a dark purple pappus in a population in Gyirong County (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/njb.00574" author="Tang, M" journalOrPublisher="Nordic Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="824 - 835" refId="B12" refString="Tang, M, Ren, C, Yang, QE, 2014. Parasenecio chenopodiifolius (Compositae - Senecioneae) is a Synotis and conspecific with S. otophylla based on evidence from morphology, cytology and ITS/ETS sequence data. Nordic Journal of Botany 32 (6): 824 - 835, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/njb.00574" title="Parasenecio chenopodiifolius (Compositae - Senecioneae) is a Synotis and conspecific with S. otophylla based on evidence from morphology, cytology and ITS / ETS sequence data." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/njb.00574" volume="32" year="2014">Tang et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
), but such variation is rather atypical in the species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="M. Tang, C. Ren &amp; Q. E. Yang" authorityYear="2014" baseAuthorityName="DC." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Synotis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Synotis chenopodiifolia" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chenopodiifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Synotis chenopodiifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a plant to 80-180 cm with triangular-ovate or triangular-hastate leaves and a capitulum with 5 phyllaries, 2 or 3(-4) disk florets, and it obviously differs from the leaf characters and capitulum characters as seen in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. panzhouensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="panzhouensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">S. panzhouensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
Morphologically, following the characters and delimitation of 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/4110124" author="Jeffrey, C" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="205 - 446" refId="B3" refString="Jeffrey, C, Chen, YL, 1984. Taxonomic studies on the tribe Senecioneae (Compositae) of Eastern Asia. Kew Bulletin 39 (2): 205 - 446, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/4110124" title="Taxonomic studies on the tribe Senecioneae (Compositae) of Eastern Asia." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/4110124" volume="39" year="1984">Jeffrey and Chen (1984)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Tang, M" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Gansu Agricultural University" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" refId="B8" refString="Tang, M, 2014. A Systematic Study of the Genus Synotis (Compositae-Senecioneae). PhD thesis. University of Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing. [In Chinese]" title="A Systematic Study of the Genus Synotis (Compositae-Senecioneae). PhD thesis. University of Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing. [In Chinese]" year="2014">Tang (2014)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. panzhouensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="panzhouensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">S. panzhouensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is best referred to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Synotis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Synotis subsp. ser." order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="series" section="Synotis" series="Synotis" species="panzhouensis" subSpecies="ser.">Synotis sect. Synotis ser. Synotis</taxonomicName>
due to the leaves gathered at the apex of the vegetative stem and its terminal inflorescence.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="iucn red list category">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">IUCN Red List Category.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
<taxonomicName authorityName="M. Tang &amp; H. L. Zheng" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Synotis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Synotis panzhouensis" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="panzhouensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Synotis panzhouensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in a single location with an extremely small population in Panzhou, southwestern Guizhou, China. Due to the remote distance and difficult and dangerous accessibility to the type locality, the population was not disturbed by human activity and currently appears to be growing very well. However, according to our observation, the population comprises no more than 100 plants, and with a small geographical range of no more than 1000 m2, we recommend that 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. panzhouensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="panzhouensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">S. panzhouensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
be categorized as Critically Endangered (CR) using criteria B and C following the IUCN Red List categories (
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Gansu Agricultural University" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" publicationUrl="https://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B7" refString="IUCN, 2019. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria version 14 [EB/OL]. 2020-04-10. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee. https://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" title="Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria version 14 [EB / OL]. 2020 - 04 - 10. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee." url="https://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2019">IUCN 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
